Revised differential diagnosis.

Pylus

is differentiated from 

Apopylus

as follows: Eyes with ocular margin raised (

) (not raised in 

Apopylus

); antennal club compact (

) (loose in 

Apopylus

); terminal palpomeres relatively small in relation to head size (

) (notably large in 

Apopylus

); prothorax strongly tuberculate laterally (

) (tubercle weak to moderate in 

Apopylus

); pronotal disc with isolated deep foveolate punctures (

) (

Apopylus

with dense matrix of shallow crater-like impressions); mesocoxal cavities wide open laterally (not confirmed in 

P. cruslumus

               comb. nov.
, 

P. kolibaci

               comb. nov.
or 

P. nactus

               comb. nov.
) (closed to narrowly open in 

Apopylus

); elytral apical margin plain, without beads or serration (

) (

Apopylus

with beaded serration); punctation of elytral disc typically with two minute internal nodules (

) (four nodules in 

Apopylus

), sometimes with a third, seta-associated nodule on the anterior edge of some punctures. Putative synapomorphies supporting monophyly of 

Pylus

in relation to 

Apopylus

include antennal club more compact (see 
Bartlett 2021
).

